We hope you will join us for the final show of our 8-week series, "It Takes a Village." Thank you to Black Education For New Orleans and The Education Trust for partnering with us over the past 8 weeks. Our radio series has truly been a wonderful forum and safe space where we have talked through REAL concerns that affect parents, children, educators and our overall community as it relates to this pandemic.

This week, we turn our attention to how we can best accommodate students with learning exceptionalities during remote learning. We hope you'll tune into WBOK 1230AM this Thursday, Sept. 3, at 9:00a.m. as we discuss this topic with local parents and education experts.

shared_text:
Education Research Alliance for New Orleans was live.
August 19 at 11:59 AM ¬∑

In August 2020, New Orleanians will mark the 15th anniversary of Hurricane Katrina. The city has changed immensely in the past fifteen years, but perhaps no other sector has changed more than K-12 education. With this anniversary, we again find ourselves in the midst of a crisis with many potential changes on the horizon. How did schools respond to the COVID-19 crisis last spring and this fall? How will the switch to remote learning change schooling for years to come? What more can we do to be resilient during and after the COVID crisis?

To discuss these questions, the Education Research Alliance for New Orleans is convening a virtual panel moderated by Douglas Harris, professor of economics at Tulane and director of ERA-New Orleans. Participants are Grisela Alejandro Jackson, 5th District Orleans Parish School Board Member; Dr. Liz Marcell Williams, CEO, Center for Resilience; Jamar McKneely, CEO, InspireNOLA Charter Schools; Allison Moultrie, parent leader at Our Voice Nuestra Voz; and Dr. Derrick White, Director of Secondary Performance & Accountability, L.B. Landry High School.

As we all know, times are fluid and much information about the 2020-2021 academic year is still unknown and expected to change as we move into different phases. We'd like to share our Phase 2 options for the reopening of our schools. Algiers Charter families, please check your email for additional details on our reopening plan.

This plan is based on guidelines released by the Louisiana Department of Education (LDOE), NOLA Public Schools (NOLA-PS), Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) as well as guidance by the Algiers Charter Family First: COVID-19 Recovery Task Force which was created in May. #algierscharter

post_text:
TODAY is more than just the last day of school at Algiers Charter. Today, May 20, 2020, is the day our senior class of 2020 had been counting down since the first day of their senior year. May 20, 2020 is the day our seniors were most anticipating from the beginning. It's the date that motivated them to get their school work done, study harder and keep their heads up high despite the challenges. It's the date that would celebrate all of their sweat and tears during their high school years.

Well, that day, today still means something to our seniors. Even though we're not gathered today to celebrate our seniors walking across the stage in a large auditorium to receive their high school diploma, today, we still celebrate YOU! üéì #AlgiersCharter #chargingbuccaneers #seniorclassof2020
